DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "PGML.pl",
  "answerHints.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl",
);

##############################################

Context("LimitedNumeric");

$a=random(5,9,1);
$b=random(2,$a-1,1);
$c=random(1,10,1);
$d=random(1,10,1);
$e=random(2,5,1);
do {$f=random(2,5,1);} until ($e!=$f);

$ans = $a-$b*($c-($d+$e*$f));
$ans=Compute($ans);

##############################################

TEXT(beginproblem());

BEGIN_PGML

Evaluate the following.

    [`` [$a]-[$b] [ [$c]-([$d]+[$e]\cdot[$f])]=  ``][________]{$ans}

END_PGML

##############################################

$brackets = "[ ]";

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

The bracket [$brackets] and parentheses ( ) have the same purpose. We usually use [$brackets] when ( ) are already used in the problem, so we can tell which pair are which.

    [``
\begin{aligned}[t]
   &\phantom{={}} [$a]-[$b] [ [$c]-([$d]+[$e]\cdot[$f])] \\
   &= [$a]-[$b] [ [$c]-([$d]+[$e*$f])] \\
   &= [$a]-[$b] [ [$c]-[$d+$e*$f] ] \\
   &= [$a]-[$b] [ [$c-$d-$e*$f] ]\\
   &= [$a]-[$b*($c-$d-$e*$f)] \\
   &= [$ans]
\end{aligned}
    ``]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

